---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="CIBIL Score for Credit Card | Minimum Score & Approval | TrueCred Loan Expert">

<!-- Page Hero -->
  <section class="page-hero">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="breadcrumb">
        <a href="/">Home</a>
        <span>/</span>
        <a href="/pages/credit-score">Credit Score</a>
        <span>/</span>
        <span>CIBIL Score for Credit Card</span>
      </div>
      <h1>CIBIL Score for <span class="gradient-text">Credit Card</span></h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">Understand the minimum CIBIL score required for different types of credit cards, how your score determines your credit limit, and tips to get approved faster.</p>
      <div class="hero-highlights">
        <div class="highlight-item">
          <i class="fas fa-credit-card"></i>
          <span>Basic Cards: 650+</span>
        </div>
        <div class="highlight-item">
          <i class="fas fa-gem"></i>
          <span>Premium Cards: 750+</span>
        </div>
        <div class="highlight-item">
          <i class="fas fa-lock"></i>
          <span>Secured Cards: Any Score</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Page Content -->
  <section class="page-content">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="content-grid">

        <!-- Main Content -->
        <div class="content-main">

          <!-- Overview -->
          <div class="content-section">
            <div class="section-header">
              <span class="section-tag">Overview</span>
              <h2>How CIBIL Score Affects Credit Card Approval</h2>
            </div>
            <p>Your CIBIL score plays a decisive role in determining which credit cards you can qualify for and what credit limit you'll receive. Credit card issuers use your score as the primary screening criterion — it tells them how likely you are to repay borrowed money on time.</p>
            <p>Unlike secured loans where collateral reduces the lender's risk, credit cards are entirely unsecured. This means issuers are more selective about whom they approve. A higher CIBIL score not only gets you approved but also qualifies you for premium cards with better rewards, higher limits, and exclusive perks like airport lounge access and travel insurance.</p>
            <p>Different categories of credit cards have different minimum score requirements. Basic and entry-level cards may accept scores as low as 650, while super-premium cards from banks like HDFC, AMEX, and Citi typically require 800+ scores with high income levels.</p>
          </div>

          <!-- Score Requirements Table -->
          <div class="content-section">
            <div class="section-header">
              <span class="section-tag">Requirements</span>
              <h2>CIBIL Score Requirements by Card Category</h2>
            </div>
            <p>Different types of credit cards have varying CIBIL score thresholds. Here's a comprehensive breakdown to help you identify which cards match your current score.</p>
            <table class="rate-table">
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Card Category</th>
                  <th>Minimum CIBIL Score</th>
                  <th>Typical Credit Limit</th>
                  <th>Key Benefits</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Secured Credit Cards</strong></td>
                  <td><span style="color: #22c55e; font-weight: 600;">No minimum</span></td>
                  <td>80–100% of FD amount</td>
                  <td>Credit building, basic rewards</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Basic/Entry-Level</strong></td>
                  <td><span style="color: #3b82f6; font-weight: 600;">650–700</span></td>
                  <td>₹25,000 – ₹1 Lakh</td>
                  <td>Basic cashback, fuel surcharge waiver</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Mid-Range/Rewards</strong></td>
                  <td><span style="color: #3b82f6; font-weight: 600;">700–750</span></td>
                  <td>₹1 Lakh – ₹3 Lakh</td>
                  <td>Reward points, movie discounts</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Premium Cards</strong></td>
                  <td><span style="color: #f59e0b; font-weight: 600;">750–800</span></td>
                  <td>₹3 Lakh – ₹10 Lakh</td>
                  <td>Lounge access, travel insurance</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Super Premium/Luxury</strong></td>
                  <td><span style="color: #f97316; font-weight: 600;">800+</span></td>
                  <td>₹10 Lakh+</td>
                  <td>Concierge, unlimited lounges, golf</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Co-branded Cards</strong></td>
                  <td><span style="color: #3b82f6; font-weight: 600;">680–720</span></td>
                  <td>₹50,000 – ₹2 Lakh</td>
                  <td>Brand-specific rewards, discounts</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>

          <!-- Factors -->
          <div class="content-section">
            <div class="section-header">
              <span class="section-tag">Key Factors</span>
              <h2>What Card Issuers Look for Beyond CIBIL Score</h2>
            </div>
            <p>While your CIBIL score is the primary filter, card issuers evaluate several additional factors to determine approval and credit limit.</p>
            <ul class="feature-list">
              <li>
                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i>
                <div>
                  <strong>Annual Income Level</strong>
                  <p>Premium cards require minimum annual income of ₹6–12 lakh, while super-premium cards may need ₹18 lakh+. Entry-level cards typically require just ₹2.5–4 lakh annual income for salaried individuals.</p>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li>
                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i>
                <div>
                  <strong>Existing Credit Card Usage</strong>
                  <p>If you already have a credit card with a good repayment history and reasonable utilisation, other issuers view this positively. Having 1–2 well-managed existing cards strengthens your application.</p>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li>
                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i>
                <div>
                  <strong>Employment Type & Stability</strong>
                  <p>Salaried employees of reputed companies have higher approval rates. Self-employed individuals typically need a higher income threshold and longer business vintage (2+ years) for the same card tier.</p>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li>
                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i>
                <div>
                  <strong>Existing Debt Burden</strong>
                  <p>High outstanding loan EMIs or maxed-out existing credit cards signal risk. Issuers calculate your total debt obligations against income to ensure you can manage additional credit responsibly.</p>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li>
                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i>
                <div>
                  <strong>Recent Credit Applications</strong>
                  <p>Multiple credit card applications in a short period raise red flags. Each application creates a hard inquiry that lowers your score and signals desperation for credit to other issuers.</p>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li>
                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i>
                <div>
                  <strong>Banking Relationship</strong>
                  <p>Having a savings/salary account with the issuing bank significantly boosts approval chances. Banks often offer pre-approved cards to existing customers with good transaction history and balance maintenance.</p>
                </div>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <!-- Steps -->
          <div class="content-section">
            <div class="section-header">
              <span class="section-tag">How to Apply</span>
              <h2>Steps to Get a Credit Card Based on Your Score</h2>
            </div>
            <p>Follow this strategic approach to find and apply for the right credit card that matches your CIBIL score and financial profile.</p>
            <div class="steps-grid">
              <div class="step-card">
                <div class="step-num">1</div>
                <h3>Know Your Score & Profile</h3>
                <p>Check your CIBIL score for free on TrueCred. Note your score range, annual income, and existing credit obligations. This determines which card categories you're eligible for.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="step-card">
                <div class="step-num">2</div>
                <h3>Match Cards to Your Score</h3>
                <p>Use TrueCred's card comparison tool to filter credit cards by your score range. Compare joining fees, annual charges, reward rates, and benefits before shortlisting 2–3 cards.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="step-card">
                <div class="step-num">3</div>
                <h3>Check Pre-Approved Offers</h3>
                <p>Before applying directly, check if your bank has pre-approved credit card offers for you. These have higher approval rates and often don't trigger additional hard inquiries on your report.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="step-card">
                <div class="step-num">4</div>
                <h3>Apply & Activate</h3>
                <p>Submit your application with complete documents. Most banks provide instant approval for pre-approved offers and 3–7 day processing for fresh applications. Activate your card upon receipt.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>

        <!-- Sidebar -->
        <div class="content-sidebar">

          <!-- Check Score Form -->
          <div class="sidebar-card">
            <h3><i class="fas fa-credit-card"></i> Check Card Eligibility</h3>
            <form class="sidebar-form" onsubmit="return false;">
              <div class="form-group">
                <input type="text" class="form-input" placeholder="Full Name" required>
              </div>
              <div class="form-group">
                <input type="text" class="form-input" placeholder="PAN Number" maxlength="10" required>
              </div>
              <div class="form-group">
                <input type="tel" class="form-input" placeholder="Mobile Number" maxlength="10" required>
              </div>
              <div class="form-group">
                <input type="date" class="form-input" placeholder="Date of Birth" required>
              </div>
              <button type="submit" class="btn btn-primary btn-block" style="width:100%;justify-content:center;">
                Check Eligibility <i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i>
              </button>
              <p class="form-disclaimer">
                <i class="fas fa-lock"></i> 100% safe & secure. No impact on your score.
              </p>
            </form>
          </div>

          <!-- Quick Links -->
          <div class="sidebar-card">
            <h3><i class="fas fa-link"></i> Quick Links</h3>
            <ul class="sidebar-links">
              <li><a href="/pages/credit-score"><i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i> Free Credit Score</a></li>
              <li><a href="/pages/cibil-score-pan"><i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i> CIBIL Check by PAN</a></li>
              <li><a href="/pages/increase-cibil-score"><i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i> Increase CIBIL Score</a></li>
              <li><a href="/pages/cibil-score-personal-loan"><i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i> CIBIL for Personal Loan</a></li>
              <li><a href="/pages/cibil-dispute"><i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i> Raise CIBIL Dispute</a></li>
              <li><a href="/pages/credit-cards"><i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i> Credit Cards</a></li>
              <li><a href="/pages/personal-loan"><i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i> Personal Loan</a></li>
              <li><a href="/pages/calculators"><i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i> EMI Calculators</a></li>
            </ul>
          </div>

        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ Section -->
  <section class="faq-section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-tag">FAQs</span>
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions About CIBIL Score for Credit Card</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">
            <span>Can I get a credit card with a CIBIL score of 600?</span>
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              <p>Getting an unsecured credit card with a CIBIL score of 600 is challenging but not impossible. A few options include: secured credit cards (backed by a fixed deposit — no minimum score required), co-branded cards from fintech companies, or cards from NBFCs with more lenient scoring criteria. Secured cards are the best route as they help you build credit while providing card benefits.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">
            <span>Does getting a credit card improve my CIBIL score?</span>
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              <p>Yes, a credit card can significantly improve your CIBIL score — if used responsibly. Make purchases regularly but keep utilisation below 30% of your limit. Always pay the full bill before the due date. Over time (6–12 months), this builds a positive credit history that can boost your score by 50–150 points. However, missed payments or high utilisation will damage your score instead.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">
            <span>What credit limit will I get based on my CIBIL score?</span>
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              <p>Your credit limit depends on both your CIBIL score and income. With a score of 750+ and annual income of ₹6 lakh, you might get a limit of ₹1.5–3 lakh. The same income with a 650 score might only get ₹25,000–50,000. Premium cards for high scorers with ₹15 lakh+ income can offer limits of ₹5–10 lakh or more. Your limit can increase over time with responsible usage.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">
            <span>How many credit cards should I have for a good CIBIL score?</span>
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              <p>Having 2–3 credit cards is generally optimal for your CIBIL score. Multiple cards increase your total available credit limit, which helps keep your overall utilisation ratio low. They also add to your credit mix. However, having too many cards (5+) can be difficult to manage and may lead to missed payments. The key is to use each card moderately and pay all bills on time.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">
            <span>Should I apply for a credit card upgrade or a new card?</span>
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              <p>If your CIBIL score has improved, upgrading your existing card is usually better than applying for a new one. An upgrade doesn't trigger a hard inquiry on your credit report, preserves your credit history length, and often comes with an automatic limit increase. Apply for a new card from a different issuer only if the specific benefits (rewards program, lounge access) justify the additional hard inquiry.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Page CTA -->
  <section class="page-cta">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Find the Best Credit Card for Your CIBIL Score</h2>
      <p>Check your score for free and discover credit cards you're eligible for. Get instant recommendations matched to your profile.</p>
      <a href="#" class="btn btn-primary btn-lg">
        Check Your Score <i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i>
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Footer -->

</BaseLayout>
